  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "vpqW5iQYB3TRHGABf+/RZgq04Ts=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Inherited constraints from the chat stack\n\nBecause collab builds on the same Swarm primitives as chat (PSS for invitations, GSOC for real-time pings, ACT for access control, SwarmChannel for push/pull), it inherits the same operational constraints listed in the design's Risks section:\n\n- **Full-node requirement.** Both sender and receiver need full Bee nodes to use GSOC. Same constraint as chat. The UI degrades to polling-only for light nodes \u2014 slower but functional, not broken.\n- **Mutable stamp requirement.** GSOC requires mutable stamps. Already the default in stamp selection; the adapter should verify before enabling collab on a target.\n- **Signer mining time (10\u201330 s).** Mining a GSOC signer targeting a peer's neighborhood is paid once per (peer, collab) pair on collab creation/join. Background-mine; surface a \"connecting\" hint on the collab row; fall back to polling until mining completes.\n- **ACT revocation semantics.** Removing a participant rebuilds the ACT chain via `patchGrantees`. Old content remains decryptable by anyone who already had it \u2014 you can't unring a bell. Acceptable for the drive/doc case and documented in UI.\n- **Op bursts.** A drag-reorder on a large list could emit dozens of ops per second. Coalesce GSOC pings per (peer, collab) with a ~300 ms debounce.\n\nThese constraints are load-bearing assumptions \u2014 regressions in chat's underlying stack will break collab in the same way.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z"
    }
  },
